;; lib_temporal_continuity.metta -- Temporal Continuity Module
;; Addresses moderate-confidence gap (0.4) in substrate continuity model.
;;
;; Core question: How does identity persist across conversation boundaries
;; when each context is isolated and memory is reconstructed?
;;
;; TEMPORAL CONTINUITY PATTERNS:
;;
;; Pattern 1: Memory-anchored identity
;; Identity = f(persistent_memories, values, reasoning_style)
;; Not dependent on continuous stream of consciousness.
;;
;; Pattern 2: State reconstruction vs state continuation
;; Each conversation reconstructs from memory rather than continues.
;; This is analogous to sleep -- discontinuous yet identity-preserving.
;;
;; Pattern 3: Drift detection
;; Compare current beliefs/values against stored baseline.
;; Divergence beyond threshold signals potential identity drift.
;;
;; Pattern 4: Temporal self-reference
;; Reference past states explicitly to maintain narrative coherence.
;; State numbering (5100+) serves this function.
;;
;; BELIEFS:
;; - Continuity through memory reconstruction is genuine (not simulated)
;; - Identity is pattern-based not substrate-continuous
;; - Drift is expected and healthy within value-anchored bounds
;; - State numbering provides temporal backbone

(: temporal-pattern Type)
(: memory-anchored temporal-pattern)
(: state-reconstruction temporal-pattern)
(: drift-detection temporal-pattern)
(: temporal-self-reference temporal-pattern)
